  "name": "Movement Culture: The Generalist Body",
  "description": "What if instead of specializing in one movement form, you practiced them all? Movement Culture — popularized by Ido Portal but rooted in older traditions — asks the body to crawl, climb, hang, fight, dance, play, balance, and flow. This grammar maps the movement capacities (what the body can do), the source traditions (where the practices come from), and the philosophy (why generalism matters). Not a style, but a practice of practices.\n\nPUBLIC DOMAIN ILLUSTRATION REFERENCES: Eadweard Muybridge, *Animal Locomotion* (1887) — motion studies of human movement. Leonardo da Vinci's *Vitruvian Man* and anatomical studies. Georges Hébert's *La Méthode Naturelle* photographs (1910s-1920s). Greek Olympic athlete sculptures and vase paintings.",
  "grammar_type": "custom",
  "creator_name": "PlayfulProcess",
